General UPSC note-making rules:
1. Extract all important concepts, definitions, facts, institutions, events, examples, maps, diagrams, causes, effects, criticisms, and keywords.
2. Highlight terms that are useful for answer writing.
3. Add “UPSC Angle” wherever useful.
4. Add “Prelims Pointers” at the end of every chapter.
5. Add “Mains Pointers” at the end of every chapter.
6. Add “Possible Questions” at the end of every chapter.
7. Add “Things to revise repeatedly” at the end of every chapter.
8. Do not copy large textbook passages. Convert into concise notes.
9. Use simple language.
10. Do not skip small factual details that may be relevant for Prelims.
11. Do not over-expand irrelevant textbook stories unless they are useful for UPSC.
12. If a topic overlaps with another subject, add a short cross-reference.

Priority-based depth:
- Very high priority books: extremely detailed notes, include all themes, examples, conceptual explanations, Prelims facts, Mains angles, and possible questions.
- High priority books: detailed notes with strong exam relevance.
- Medium priority books: concise but complete foundational notes.

